ol.li:
Configure the build script to use the non official  gwt-gradle-plugin :


buildscript {
    repositories {
		maven (){ url 'http://repo.putnami.org' }
	}
	dependencies {
		classpath 'de.richsource.gradle.plugins:gwt-gradle-plugin:0.4-PWT_patched'
	}
}

Add the Maven central repository to download common dependencies and the Putnami maven repository to download the PWT artifacts :


repositories {
	mavenCentral()
	maven (){ url 'http://repo.putnami.org' }
}

Now we add the PWT dependency :


dependencies {
	compile 'fr.putnami.pwt:pwt:@releaseVersion@'
}

In order to use the gwt-gradle-plugin, we have to apply it and configure it :


apply plugin: 'gwt'

gwt {
	gwtVersion = '2.6.1'

	// Modules used in production
	modules = ['fr.putnami.pwt.tutorial.Tutorial']
	// Modules used in dev mode and super dev mode.
	devModules = ['fr.putnami.pwt.tutorial.TutorialDev']

	superDev {
		noPrecompile=true
	}

	// You can skip it if you won't use it
	// If you add it, you'll have to apply the jetty plugin first.
	gwtDev {
		// Allows to debug with the standard Dev mode
		// ( no more supported on Chrome for Linux or on Firefox)
		jvmArgs('-Xdebug',  '-Xrunjdwp:transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=n,address=8000')
	}
}

Finally, we apply the jetty plugin to launch the web app, and configure a custom task to run the application with draft GWT compilation :
apply plugin: 'jetty'
task jettyDraftWar(type: JettyRunWar) { dependsOn draftWar dependsOn.remove('war') webApp=draftWar.archivePath }

First we create the fr.putnami.pwt.tutorial.client.TutorialApp java Class, implementing EntryPoint :


package fr.putnami.pwt.tutorial.client;

import com.google.gwt.core.client.EntryPoint;
import com.google.gwt.user.client.ui.RootPanel;

import fr.putnami.pwt.core.widget.client.OutputStaticText;

public class TutorialApp implements EntryPoint {

	@Override
	public void onModuleLoad() {
		RootPanel.get().add(new OutputStaticText("Hello Putnami"));
	}
}
